{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e886d95a-c8cc-4a36-b0ef-f05971d6bc9d","content":"Here's the recommended approach for collecting a trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Exec into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present):**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find the process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect the trace:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n**To copy the trace off the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't on the PATH in the container, use the full path (`$env:USERPROFILE\\.dotnet\\tools\\dotnet-trace`).\n- For GC/allocation analysis, use `--profile gc-collect` instead.\n- If you can't install tools in the container, you can alternatively enable **EventPipe** via environment variables (`DOTNET_EnableEventPipe=1`, `DOTNET_EventPipeOutputPath=C:\\trace.nettrace`) and restart the pod — it will emit a trace on shutdown.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"36d63493-207e-4ae9-9e3f-a4607b7c6ce8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I'll provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":413},"id":"b3d5c991-1ce3-4653-92ff-982cd62a1501","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:49:34.408Z","parentId":"7342b966-fc5f-4b42-aef1-ebc348dae889"}
